The '''All-America Bridge''' in [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]], [[Ohio]] is a [[viaduct]] carrying [[Ohio State Route 261]] over the [[Little Cuyahoga River]] that splits into a [[one-way pair]]. Constructed 1981&ndash;1982,<ref name=2009basics>{{cite news |first= |last= |format= |coauthors= |title=Bridge Basics |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=12C7E079D2D384E0&p_docnum=68&p_queryname=2 |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2009-12-06 |accessdate=2010-04-05 }}</ref><ref name=pd>{{cite news |first=Karen |last=Farkas |coauthors= |title=Valley View I-480 bridge barrier replacement put off for two years |url=http://blog.cleveland.com/metro/2009/08/valley_view_i480_bridge_barrie.html |work=[[The Plain Dealer]] |publisher= |date=2009-08-25 |accessdate=2009-08-27 }}</ref> the bridge was named in recognition of Akron's past [[All-America City Award]]s<ref name=2009basics/> and is also locally known as the Y-Bridge.<ref name=2009suicidemain>{{cite news |first=Mark J. |last=Price |format= |coauthors= |title='Suicide Bridge' Spans Lives |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=12C7E079CFB43F98&p_docnum=2&p_queryname=4 |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2009-12-06 |accessdate=2010-04-05 }}</ref> The bridge is 134 feet tall in its highest location.<ref name=2009basics/>

The bridge's predecessor, the 1922 North Hill Viaduct, was closed in 1977<ref name=2009basics/> after a collapse killed three.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}} The poem ''Under The North Hill Viaduct'' was written by [[Rita Dove]].

Over its existence, the bridge has been the site of at least one suicide a year (police records are incomplete).<ref>{{cite news |first=Denise |last=Grollmus |format= |coauthors= |title=Suicide Bridge |url=http://www.clevescene.com/cleveland/suicide-bridge/Content?oid=1490951 |work=[[Cleveland Scene|Scene]] |publisher= |date=2005-06-08 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref> From 1997 until December 3, 2009, 29 people committed suicide by jumping from the bridge.<ref name=2009suicidemain/><ref name=2009suicideside>{{cite news |first= |last= |format= |coauthors= |title='Suicide Bridge' |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=12C7E079D4936138&p_docnum=1&p_queryname=4 |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2009-12-06 |accessdate=2010-04-05 }}</ref>

In 2009, it was announced that $1 million to $1.5 million would be spent to fence the bridge using [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|federal economic stimulus funds]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Cooper |coauthors= |title=Soul-Searching in Akron, Ohio, Over Stimulus Use |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/06/us/06akron.html |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date=2009-05-05 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref> Fencing the bridge was controversial in Akron and the plan had previously failed to receive local support.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Warsmith |format= |coauthors=Rick Armon; Bob Downing |title=Y-Bridge Will Be Fenced |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%2012737CE60DC373E8%20)&p_docid=12737CE60DC373E8&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=12737CE60DC373E8&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=P67P50IHMTI1MTc2MDE2NS4xMjc0NjoxOjEyOjE5OC4zMC4yMjguMA&&p_multi=ABJB |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2009-03-27 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Kist |format= |coauthors= |title=West Akron couple urge Council to fence Y-Bridge |url=http://www.akron.com/akron-ohio-community-news.asp?aID=2569 |work=West Side Leader |publisher= |date=2008-06-05 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref> Previous local attempts to fence the bridge failed in 1991, 1993, 2000 and 2006.<ref>{{cite news |first=Delano R. |last=Massey |format= |coauthors= |title=City May Fence In Bridge |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%20111FAE6122D121B8%20)&p_docid=111FAE6122D121B8&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=111FAE6122D121B8&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=K6EO57DOMTI1MTc1OTg0Mi45NjcxNjoxOjEyOjE5OC4zMC4yMjguMA&&p_multi=ABJB |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2006-05-31 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Quinn |format= |coauthors= |title=Funds Are Sought For Fences Along Y-Bridge |url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%200EB62F53969128CE%20)&p_docid=0EB62F53969128CE&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=0EB62F53969128CE&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=I63L4CRDMTI1MTc1OTg1OS44NTMyMTA6MToxMjoxOTguMzAuMjI4LjA&&p_multi=ABJB |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=1993-06-22 |accessdate=2009-08-31 }}</ref> The project was expected to be completed by September 2010<ref name=pd/> but was stopped for the winter of 2010-2011.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephanie |last=Warsmith |coauthors= |title=Y-bridge to remain fully open until spring |url=http://www.ohio.com/news/top_stories/110318449.html |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2010-11-24 |accessdate=2011-02-05 }}</ref> The project was finally completed in late December 2011.<ref>{{cite news | first=Stephanie |last=Warsmith |format= |coauthors= |title=Y-Bridge project more costly, takes longer than expected; officials pleased with result |url=http://www.ohio.com/news/local/y-bridge-project-more-costly-takes-longer-than-expected-officials-pleased-with-result-1.254126 |work=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |publisher= |date=2012-01-08 |accessdate=2012-01-08}}</ref>

